While, theoretically, a resolution of the minority of the nation had no binding

The colleges of priests had great influence in politics, hence the aristocrats desired to keep the offices in their own hands. — ad populi beneficium: magistracies are often called beneficia papuli Romani. —primus instituit eto: . the interpretation of this passage is difficult. Plutarch, Life of C. Gracchus, c. 5, tells the tale of C. Gracchus, and assigns to the act a democratic purpose. Our passage certainly seems to countenance Plutarch in this, but Lange, Romische Alterthume1112, 443, denies that the act had any political aim. He connects it with achange in the voting at public assemblies. This originally took place in the comitium, which formed a small part of what was ordinarily called the sarum. Lange thinks that when the voting was transferred from the comitium to the sarpta (enclosures) the speakers naturally turned their backs on the comitium and faced the saepta, the rastra being placed between them. The matter is far from clear, and Lange's explanation seems scarcely to be consistent with this passage. - agerecum populo: the technical phrase for the laying oi matters before the people in their assemblies. — vendibilem: ‘plausible’; lit. ‘salabiet So Brut. 174 vendibilis aratar; Fin. 1, 12 nam ut sint illa ventiibiliara, hacc uberiora certe sunt. — praetore me: as the regular age ior the praetorship was 40, Laelius was probably born about 186 Β. c. — re...auctoritate: since Laelius was not consul, he carried his case on its merite and not from the auctoritas conferred by office, which was then not summa.
